Question: Spring request mapping catching part of uri to PathVariable: :I need something similar to enter link description hereSo my path would be: /something/else/and/some/moreI would like to map it like so:@RequestMapping(value="/something/**", method=RequestMethod.GET)public String handleRequest(String theRestOfPath){ /***/ }Or@RequestMapping(value="/something/**", method=RequestMethod.GET)public String handleRequest(String[] theRestOfPathArr){ /***/ }The thing is ... I would like everything matched by ** to be passed to the method either:1. as a string (theRestOfPath = "/else/and/some/more"),2. or as an array (theRestOfPathArr = ["else","and","some","more"]).  The number of path variables can vary, so I can't do:@RequestMapping(value="/something/{a}/{b}/{c}", method=RequestMethod.GET)public String handleRequest(String a, String b, String c){ /***/ }Is there a way to do that?Thanks :)  ---EDIT---The solution I ended up with:  @RequestMapping(value = "/something/**", method = RequestMethod.GET)@ResponseBodypublic TextStory getSomething(HttpServletRequest request) {    final String URI_PATTERN = "^.*/something(/.+?)(\\.json|\\.xml)?$";    String uri = request.getRequestURI().replaceAll(URI_PATTERN, "$1");    return doSomethingWithStuff(uri);}
Please using this api: StringTokenizer.nextToken.
Answer: <<<api>>>: StringTokenizer.nextToken
<<<code>>>: 
```java
StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(theRestOfPath, "/");
String[] theRestOfPathArr = new String[st.countTokens()];
int i=0;
while (st.hasMoreTokens()) {
    theRestOfPathArr[i++] = st.nextToken();
}
```
<<<explanation>>>: The StringTokenizer class is used to break the string into tokens. The tokens are obtained by splitting the string around the delimiters. In this case, the delimiter is "/". The tokens are stored in an array.
```java
StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(theRestOfPath, "/");
String[] theRestOfPathArr = new String[st.countTokens()];
int i=0;
while (st.hasMoreTokens()) {
    theRestOfPathArr[i++] = st.nextToken();
}
```
```
Please note that theRestOfPathArr[0] will be an empty string because the leading "/" is considered as a delimiter. If you want to remove the first element, you can do so by creating a new array with a length of st.countTokens()-1.
```java
StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(theRestOfPath, "/");
String[] theRestOfPathArr = new String[st.countTokens()-1];
int i=0;
while (st.hasMoreTokens()) {
    theRestOfPathArr[i++] = st.nextToken();
}
```
```
Also, theRestOfPathArr will be null if theRestOfPath is "/". You need to handle this case in your code.
